A Republican strategy to counter the re-election of Obama
The leaders of the Republicans justify their policy with the need to fight the electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth by reaffirming that the election fraud in the US is more rare than the number of people killed by lightning.
The lawyers of the Republicans have, by the way, recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voting participation.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the US states are responsible for conducting elections in each country.
In this sense, the majority of American governments have announced new laws since 2009 that make the registration or immoral procedure difficult.
This phenomenon has gained importance after the November 2010 elections, where 675 new Republican representatives could be recorded in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced alone in 2011, which restrict the exercise of electoral rights in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo card and evidence of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce the time limits for the premature vote, declare the right to register as voters on the election day invalid, and govern the right to vote for citizens for which a court act is available.
Before the 2006 elections, no US state asked the voters to present a photo card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
In 2008, the Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana Act.
The Republican authorities hasten to extend this practice to other states.
Over the last two years, they have supported draft laws in 34 states which force voters to present a photo card.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal ID card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million voters, do not have a photograph card issued by a government authority of their state.
In addition, five million new voters do not have such an ID in 2012.
However, more than a hundred dollars are often payable to obtain the necessary ID.
The new restrictions are disproportionately affected by young people, minorities and low-income people.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years do not have the necessary photo card.
This is still enough.
Students who are regarded as voters who increase their voice for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo card issued by their institution in several countries.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting associations who choose more for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these associations for elections.
Before 2004, no state for electing asked for evidence of citizenship.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove their US citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic votes.
It is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, Republican legislators have promoted law in eight states in 2011 to abolish the registration of voters on the election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to the voters who want to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the campaign to register voters in the 2004 general elections helped to register about 10 million citizens.
Indeed, the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the share of the registration of new voters in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, the Republican legislators have adopted laws in five other states aimed at shortening the period for the early vote.
For example, at the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, although they represent only 13% of the voters of the state.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter represented only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
On the other hand, the white people representing 76% of the voters accounted for only 46% of the voters selected in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were blocked by the veto of the democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They could partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have adopted laws requiring the display of a photo card.
However, the newly introduced rules in 2012 will undoubtedly make the exercise of electoral rights difficult.
The democratic critics denounce the party political nature of the laws adopted and see them as a clear objective of influencing the results in the countries that decide for 2012.
A 2011 Brennan Centre report shows that those States that have adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required by the electoral board to win the Presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the presidential elections in 2012.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voting participation.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
