The Higgs-Boson analyzes
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs Boson has raised some attention last summer, and this for good reason.
Indeed, one believes that this Boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or "least false" statement of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists, it is not completely certain that it is really Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs Boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but there are still no data to be completely safe about it.
Still, let's assume that this is actually the Higgs, because apparently there's only a small risk of cheating, and let's look at what it is about.
There is an indispensable law in this world, which means that two objects cannot be present at the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and don't try too hard as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that it also applies to such a law: the Pauli's principle of exclusion, which means that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantum state," which in large and whole consists of some of their properties.
From that point of view, physicists divided the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens who are called Fermione and are politically obedient to the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons move, a bad gang of anarchists who are nothing sacred - in any case not this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
These Bosons are divided into two groups according to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley laboratories (which, by the way, is absolutely amazing): the Mesons that we will not treat here and the "power particles" which spread the great forces of nature and with which the Higgs-Boson would somehow be related.
However, it must be emphasised here that these Bosons are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronic, then only thanks to a Boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle," which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
If a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" exactly at this place, in about like a pebble stone that has been thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the Bosons "carriers of power."
Stable field
The same applies to the Higgs Boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" so that this Boson shows itself.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must achieve very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be scattered by a very large rock.
Therefore a huge particle accelerator such as CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is once again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, it is not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep itself at the refrigerator.
And not all particles interact equally with the Higgs field: those who do it possess a mass, while the others (like the photon) do not possess a mass.
For what can all of these research now be "good," Mrs Plamondon asks?
For science, they are used to verify the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to investigate all disparities between the observations and the forecasts of the SM.
By the way, there are many physicists who are most hoping that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and put some holes of the model.
One has to say that the latter still has major shortcomings as it does not provide an explanation for the gravity (ups!) and the dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (again up!).
However, such derogations have not yet been found in CERN.
Impact
The impact of these research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there was no.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the deceased physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first permanent laser (the first were pulled) in 1962 - has already said that the laser was at the beginning rather considered a "laboratory game."
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also come from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in the optics in 1969.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor today serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and introduced him the Nobel Prize for Physics in 2009.
Of course this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it means that you really can never know...
