It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success," "in competition with the dollar or the euro," and "similar to the traditional currencies."
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the "credits," which are used to move forward in a video game that you can win or buy (and sometimes exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is monitored and processed every time by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network buttons are simultaneously depositors of the book, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users takes place in reality between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of data related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
With the help of the contents of the file it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are available in the public accounts accounting book throughout the network.
The decisive step is to include this new transaction in this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner who is a kind of provisional central bank who has the privilege to add this additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and clear electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole is "hacked."
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number is found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If one user wants to pay twice very fast (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain without connection, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task receives 50 bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward will be halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be shared up to a hundred million, which leaves a certain margin...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with any improvement in the calculation performance.
