Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted to a ministerial meeting of the members of the European Space Agency ESA as the twentieth member of this Space Authority. Poland is thus the second member of the former East Block (after the Czech Republic, who became ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The path of Poland to space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos was concerned with space, not always understanding.
For example, I recall the presentation by A. Šternfeld of 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "entrance to cosmonautics."
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) made the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the Prix REP Hirsch, founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch in 1934.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's recognised contribution to the development of space was appreciated, among other things, by the name of one of the crater on the Earth side of the Moon after him.
In 1925 a railway draisine was built in Poland for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to start or to brake the wire.
The information on this is exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with missile-operated shots.
The research carried out by the Institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It is clear from the documents provided that research has been advanced to the stage of practical tests.
The research was then interrupted by the invasion of the German army.
In 1937, in the specialist press, the design of a photoelectric hunt draket from Ing. Rohoziński appeared, and in the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" of the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the rocket drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects for military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komit Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work his work was completed from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society takes place in 1954 in the November edition of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of space are dedicated.
The article of Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the establishment of a space company.
At the time there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was expected that the exploration of space would have the future.
In its early 1956, the Polish Space Company PTA tried to join the International Federation for Space, founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a regular member in the autumn of 1956.
In the following year, the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Deputy Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He had this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has played a major role in the development of the extremely successful meteorological missile (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish missile for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first start took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighs not entirely 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 began in the Błędów desert flight tests with the two-stage raket RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight height of up to 14,5 km and be used for the observation of highwind.
However, further development was stopped in 1962.
The first RM missile was developed in 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage raket, its total length was 510 cm and its starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of rocket were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differ from one another in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B of 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C of 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight height for all three types was 37 km.
In the years 1965 to 1968, the Meteor 2 missile was developed at the aerospace Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a utility load of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
After that, the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which followed two years later the creation of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites under the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second Intercosmonaut after the Czechoslovakia Vladimír Remek.
