Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert for US-European relations, Berlin thus balances on a narrow diplomatic level.
German wave: At the beginning of the week Germany had signalled that it would vote against the request for an observer status of the Palestinians in the United Nations.
But then Berlin retained itself.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be careful due to its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it was about setting up an aircraft ban zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is just transforming its foreign policy away from a policy that has been managed by the United States to a German foreign policy.
It is also worrying that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
So the Germans find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that they are still working on their role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy such as France or the United Kingdom.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It demonstrates the willingness to take positions in national interests which are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other major powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests had an impact on the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
Firstly, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
It must therefore be cautious not to face the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
It certainly matters.
But I wouldn't want to weigh too much, that's not a completely unilateral relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining in important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe and even in the United States there is a great understanding of the German position.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic breakdown as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will take a certain amount of respect with this.
Because it signals that it is being taken seriously as an international player and that its interests need to be considered.
There are various views in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
On the other hand, the United States has clearly expressed its support for a veto.
Are there differences between the United States and many European nations?
Because of American internal policy, these differences have always existed.
I believe that the government under Obama has, in secret, quite a great deal of understanding for the European position.
But because of the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, represent this position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as large as they always appear.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanjahu, Obama is not very enthusiastic about Netanjahus policy.
Is it difficult for Germany to agree on its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand and on the position of the main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not currently the case.
So they can't be part of a wider line and instead need to drive things out of their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
This is, of course, not easy for Germany, because of the relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive issue.
But I believe that the Germans are clear that they need to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself in the role of important international players - does Germany want to take a leading role at all?
Or does Germany still have a difficult leadership role?
Germany is not used to it, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
For example, when we look at the euro crisis, every time Germany takes a greater role, various anti-German feelings will be free.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this way, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the USA.
It must be susceptible to various neighbours and opinions, and that is not easy.
Now the US's influence on European policy is constantly decreasing, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment, who else is there?
The Germans will simply have to play a greater role.
Even if they don't like it, it's unpleasant for them and makes them much more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute in which academics and political experts from Europe and North America are jointly researching the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, specializing in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
